				<td colspan="2"><span>Doesn't matter which order you slow in, the aggro will be the same regardless of whether the spell landed, resisted, or bounced. There would be a slight variation in the case of Assonance, due to the damage per tick it would do, but you're talking tens of aggro, nothing truely important. 
<br />

<br />
Likewise, the same is true for charm. Theoretically you could use a charm that caps low enough to be resisted by default (Your target is too high a level for your charm spell! /n Your target has resisted your Solon's Song of the Sirens spell!) solely for the purpose of maintaining aggro. Mind you, I only now realized this and have yet to try any tests with it. It is possible that charm is considerably more aggro after the break than on a simple resist, but it is worth the attempt I think.</span></td>
